 an ONNX model (qwen2.5-0.5b-instruct-int4.onnx) into `onnxruntime-web`. However, your current implementation is a **structural placeholder**. It performs a single forward pass, extracts state, but returns a hardcoded string rather than generating tokens organically.\n\n  Line 25: **Fix:** The ONNX model must output `present_key_values`, which you feed back into the next iteration as `past_key_values`. \n\n  Line 29: **Fix:** You must add the `webgpu` Execution Provider (EP). ONNX Runtime Web v1.17+ supports `webgpu` natively and it offers a 300% performance boost over WASM on standard laptops.\n\n  Line 39: To build your moat, you don't need a 70B parameter model. You need highly aggressive, INT4-quantized Small Language Models (0.3B - 3.8B parameters) converted to the **ONNX** format. At INT4, a 1B parameter model consumes roughly 600MB of RAM — perfectly viable for a student's Celeron laptop.\n\n  Line 51: - **Architecture:** ONNX standard (`.onnx`) \n\n  Line 52: - **Quantization:** INT4 (specifically AWQ or GPTQ translated to ONNX INT4, or natively exported to ONNX q4f16)\n\n  Line 102: 1. Use Hugging Face's `optimum-cli` to export Qwen 2.5 0.5B to ONNX INT4.\n\n  Line 111: By implementing your own ONNX-WebGPU autoregressive loop, you **completely decouple LAMPForge from Microsoft's `window.ai` and Chrome's `prompt-API` release cycles.** \n\n  Line 113: You use `window.ai` opportunistically when it's there (Zero Cost, Zero Download), but when it isn't—or when the hardware policy blocks it—your custom ONNX WebGPU engine kicks in, loads Qwen2.5-0.5B from the OPFS cache, and executes the blueprint generation organically.\n\n\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\RandD\\market_intelligence_browser_ai_platform_stability.md:\n  Line 14: **The bottom line:** Your core runtime (WASM + Service Workers + OPFS + ONNX Runtime Web) is permanent. Your AI acceleration layer (WebNN + `window.ai`) is not yet standardised and must be treated as an opportunistic advantage with a fallback architecture — which you already have.\n\n  Line 39: | **Your dependency** | PHP-WASM (browser PDE runtime), ONNX Runtime Web (inference engine), `onnxruntime-web` npm package |\n\n  Line 41: **Assessment:** WASM is as permanent as HTML. The W3C explicitly states backward compatibility as a design principle. Your PHP-WASM and ONNX Runtime Web dependencies will never break due to the underlying WASM standard changing. This is the foundation of your entire browser-native architecture.\n\n  Line 76: ### 4. ONNX Runtime Web\n\n  Line 84: | **Your dependency** | `forge-ai.ts` (ONNX router), `edge-ai.ts` (capability detection), `forge-onnx.ts` (inference) |\n\n  Line 86: **Assessment:** ONNX Runtime Web is the safest AI inference dependency in the browser ecosystem. MIT-licensed, Microsoft-maintained, backward-compat guaranteed, semver-versioned. Your INT4 quantised models will load in ONNX Runtime Web v2.x, v3.x, and beyond. The WASM backend is your permanent fallback even if WebNN and WebGPU evolve.\n\n  Line 131: - Your fallback to ONNX Runtime Web WASM backend ensures you function without WebNN\n\n  Line 183: **Your architecture is correct:** You detect `window.ai` as an opportunistic Tier 0, with ONNX Runtime Web as the stable fallback. Do not hard-depend on `window.ai` existing in any future browser version. Your `inferWithBrowserAI()` function correctly returns `null` on failure, triggering the fallback cascade.\n\n  Line 228: | ONNX Runtime Web | Microsoft (MIT) | Semver quarterly | ✅ Explicit | N/A (npm) | Critical | 🟩 BEDROCK |\n\n  Line 246: 1. **WASM + ONNX Runtime Web** = permanent local inference capability. Even if WebNN and `window.ai` disappear tomorrow, your INT4 quantised models run via ONNX Runtime Web's WASM backend. This never breaks.\n\n  Line 256:   WASM → ONNX Runtime Web → INT4 model → inference result\n\n  Line 269: - \"Browser-native AI inference via WebAssembly and ONNX Runtime\" — 🟩 permanent\n\n  Line 285: