      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\\\spec\\\\FINOPS.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\spec\\FINOPS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # SDTP `.forge` Protocol - FinOps Governance Specification\n2: \n3: **Financial Operations and Cost Governance Reference**\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Status\n8: \n9: **Draft v1.0** - Aligned with `SPECIFICATION.md` Draft v1.0.\n10: \n11: ---\n12: \n13: ## Abstract\n14: \n15: This document specifies the financial operations (FinOps) subsystem of the SDTP Supervisor. The FinOps subsystem exists to ensure that AI-assisted learning features remain cost-transparent, cost-bounded, and educationally appropriate. It addresses a critical equity concern: students from lower-income backgrounds, and educational institutions with constrained budgets, must be able to use AI tooling without incurring unexpected cloud costs.\n16: \n17: The FinOps proxy intercepts all inference API calls, applies pre-call budget checks, records post-call costs in an append-only ledger, and activates graceful degradation when configured budget limits are approached or exceeded.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## Table of Contents\n22: \n23: 1. [Why FinOps Matters in Education](#1-why-finops-matters-in-education)\n24: 2. [Cost Model](#2-cost-model)\n25: 3. [Budget Enforcement Algorithm](#3-budget-enforcement-algorithm)\n26: 4. [Ledger Format](#4-ledger-format)\n27: 5. [Alert Delivery Mechanism](#5-alert-delivery-mechanism)\n28: 6. [Kill Switch Behaviour](#6-kill-switch-behaviour)\n29: 7. [Session vs Monthly Accounting](#7-session-vs-monthly-accounting)\n30: 8. [Provider Cost Table](#8-provider-cost-table)\n31: 9. [Accounting API](#9-accounting-api)\n32: 10. [Configuration Reference](#10-configuration-reference)\n33: 11. [Audit and Compliance](#11-audit-and-compliance)\n34: \n35: ---\n36: \n37: ## 1. Why FinOps Matters in Education\n38: \n39: ### 1.1 The Equity Problem\n40: \n41: Modern software development increasingly involves AI coding assistants, code review tools, and generative documentation. Students who train with these tools develop skills directly transferable to professional environments. However, cloud-based AI inference carries per-call costs that can accumulate rapidly - and unpredictably - during extended coding sessions.\n42: \n43: For **first-generation students** entering higher education, unexpected charges on a personal credit card or a prepaid API key can be a significant financial shock. For many students in further education colleges, the choice between using AI tools and meeting basic living costs is not hypothetical.\n44: \n45: For **educational institutions**, particularly further education colleges and sixth forms operating under constrained government funding, uncontrolled AI API spend across an entire cohort can rapidly exhaust discretionary IT budgets. A class of 30 students each making 50 inference calls per session at £0.0001 per call generates costs that are individually trivial but collectively material when multiplied across a full academic year.\n46: \n47: ### 1.2 The Pedagogical Problem\n48: \n49: Beyond cost, unbounded AI inference creates a pedagogical risk: students who have unlimited, friction-free access to AI generation of code may produce assessable work that does not reflect their own understanding. Budget limits serve a dual purpose - they are both a financial control and a pedagogical control, encouraging deliberate, purposeful use of AI assistance rather than unreflective generation.\n50: \n51: ### 1.3 The SDTP Response\n52: \n53: The SDTP FinOps subsystem addresses these concerns by:\n54: \n55: 1. **Defaulting to zero cloud spend** (`max_monthly_cloud: 0.00`) - no cloud inference without an explicit budget decision by the institution or teacher\n56: 2. **Preferring local inference** (`inference.prefer: local`) - on-device models (Foundry Local, ONNX WebNN) are free and private\n57: 3. **Making costs visible** - the Evidence Panel displays running cost totals in real time\n58: 4. **Enforcing budgets deterministically** - the Kill Switch is algorithmic, not advisory\n59: 5. **Supporting institutional oversight** - the ledger format enables per-student, per-cohort cost reporting\n60: \n61: ---\n62: \n63: ## 2. Cost Model\n64: \n65: ### 2.1 Estimation Approach\n66: \n67: The FinOps proxy estimates the cost of a pending inference call **before** the call is made. This pre-call estimate is used for budget enforcement. A post-call reconciliation corrects the estimate using actual token counts from the provider's response.\n68: \n69: **Estimation formula:**\n70: \n71: ```\n72: estimated_cost = (prompt_tokens / 1000) * provider_input_price_per_1k\n73:                + (max_completion_tokens / 1000) * provider_output_price_per_1k\n74: ```\n75: \n76: Where:\n77: - `prompt_tokens` is computed by the proxy using the same tokeniser as the target provider (tiktoken for OpenAI-compatible APIs; provider-specific tokenisers otherwise)\n78: - `max_completion_tokens` is the value of `max_tokens` in the request payload; if absent, the proxy uses a conservative default of 256 tokens\n79: - `provider_input_price_per_1k` and `provider_output_price_per_1k` are fetched from the Registry pricing table and cached with a 1-hour TTL\n80: \n81: **Post-call reconciliation:**\n82: \n83: ```\n84: actual_cost = (actual_prompt_tokens / 1000) * provider_input_price_per_1k\n85:             + (actual_completion_tokens / 1000) * provider_output_price_per_1k\n86: ```\n87: \n88: The actual cost is recorded in the ledger. The running totals used for future pre-call checks are updated with the actual cost, not the estimate. This means that if a call's actual cost exceeds the estimate (e.g., because `max_tokens` was not set and the model generated a long response), the running total is updated upwards and may trigger threshold alerts retroactively.\n89: \n90: ### 2.2 Token Counting\n91: \n92: For providers using OpenAI-compatible tokenisation (GPT-family, Llama-family via Groq/Cerebras), the proxy uses the `tiktoken` library with the `cl100k_base` encoding as a conservative approximation for all models unless a model-specific encoding is registered in the pricing table.\n93: \n94: For local providers (Foundry Local, ONNX WebNN), the cost is always `£0.00` regardless of token count. Token counts are still recorded in the ledger for pedagogical transparency.\n95: \n96: ### 2.3 Currency Conversion\n97: \n98: All monetary values are stored and compared in the currency specified by `finops.budget.currency` (default: `GBP`). Provider pricing tables in the Registry are maintained in GBP. If a provider publishes pricing in USD, the Registry converts using the exchange rate at the time of the last pricing table update. The proxy does NOT perform real-time exchange rate lookups during inference calls.\n99: \n100: ### 2.4 Cost Estimation Accuracy\n101: \n102: The proxy's cost estimates are **conservative by design**: they tend to over-estimate rather than under-estimate. This ensures that budget enforcement errs on the side of protecting the student's budget. The typical over-estimation error is less than 15% for well-formed requests with `max_tokens` set.\n103: \n104: ---\n105: \n106: ## 3. Budget Enforcement Algorithm\n107: \n108: The following pseudo-code describes the complete enforcement algorithm executed by the FinOps proxy for each inference call:\n109: \n110: ```\n111: ALGORITHM: InferenceCallEnforcement\n112: \n113: INPUT:\n114:   request         = the outbound inference API request object\n115:   config          = forge-resolved.json finops section\n116:   state           = in-memory FinOps state (running totals, call counts)\n117:   ledger          = append-only file handle\n118: \n119: PRE-CALL PHASE:\n120: ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n121: 1. provider = resolve_provider(request.url, config.inference.allowed_providers,\n122:                                             config.inference.blocked_providers)\n123: \n124:    if provider is null:\n125:      RETURN { error: \"provider_not_allowed\", provider: request.url }\n126: \n127: 2. prompt_tokens = count_tokens(request.body.messages, provider.tokenizer)\n128: \n129: 3. max_completion = request.body.max_tokens ?? 256\n130: \n131: 4. estimated_cost = estimate_cost(provider, prompt_tokens, max_completion)\n132: \n133: 5. if config.budget.max_monthly_cloud > 0:\n134:      if state.monthly_total + estimated_cost > config.budget.max_monthly_cloud:\n135:        trigger_alert(\"kill_at\", state)\n136:        activate_kill_switch(state)\n137:        RETURN { error: \"budget_exceeded\",\n138:                 monthly_total: state.monthly_total,\n139:                 limit: config.budget.max_monthly_cloud,\n140:                 currency: config.budget.currency }\n141: \n142: 6. if config.budget.max_inference_calls is set:\n143:      if state.session_call_count >= config.budget.max_inference_calls:\n144:        RETURN { error: \"call_limit_exceeded\",\n145:                 call_count: state.session_call_count,\n146:                 limit: config.budget.max_inference_calls }\n147: \n148: 7. state.pending_calls += 1\n149: \n150: EXECUTE PHASE:\n151: ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n152: 8. response = forward_request_to_provider(request)\n153: \n154: POST-CALL ACCOUNTING PHASE:\n155: ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n156: 9. actual_prompt_tokens     = response.usage.prompt_tokens\n157:    actual_completion_tokens = response.usage.completion_tokens\n158:    actual_cost              = calculate_actual_cost(provider, actual_prompt_tokens,\n159:                                                      actual_completion_tokens)\n160: \n161: 10. state.pending_calls      -= 1\n162:     state.session_total      += actual_cost\n163:     state.monthly_total      += actual_cost\n164:     state.session_call_count += 1\n165: \n166: 11. ledger_entry = {\n167:       timestamp:         now_iso8601(),\n168:       sessionId:         state.session_id,\n169:       provider:          provider.id,\n170:       model:             response.model,\n171:       promptTokens:      actual_prompt_tokens,\n172:       completionTokens:  actual_completion_tokens,\n173:       estimatedCost:     estimated_cost,\n174:       actualCost:        actual_cost,\n175:       currency:          config.budget.currency,\n176:       sessionTotal:      state.session_total,\n177:       monthlyTotal:      state.monthly_total,\n178:       callCount:         state.session_call_count\n179:     }\n180:     ledger.append(JSON.stringify(ledger_entry) + \"\\n\")\n181:     ledger.flush()\n182: \n183: THRESHOLD COMPARISON PHASE:\n184: ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n185: 12. if config.budget.max_monthly_cloud > 0:\n186:       fraction = state.monthly_total / config.budget.max_monthly_cloud\n187: \n188:       if not state.warn_alert_sent AND fraction >= config.alerts.warn_at:\n189:         dispatch_alert(\"warn\", fraction, state, config)\n190:         state.warn_alert_sent = true\n191: \n192:       if not state.kill_alert_sent AND fraction >= config.alerts.kill_at:\n193:         dispatch_alert(\"kill\", fraction, state, config)\n194:         activate_kill_switch(state)\n195:         state.kill_alert_sent = true\n196: \n197: 13. RETURN response\n198: ```\n199: \n200: ### 3.1 Provider Resolution\n201: \n202: Step 1 resolves the provider by matching the request's destination URL against a known provider registry:\n203: \n204: | URL Pattern | Provider ID |\n205: |-------------|------------|\n206: | `*api.groq.com*` | `groq` |\n207: | `*api.cerebras.ai*` | `cerebras` |\n208: | `*api.openai.com*` | `openai` |\n209: | `*api.anthropic.com*` | `anthropic` |\n210: | `*foundry.local*` or loopback to Foundry binary | `foundry-local` |\n211: | WebNN ONNX runtime (in-process) | `onnx-webnn` |\n212: \n213: If the URL does not match any known provider, the proxy applies the `blocked_providers` rule: if `allowed_providers` is set and does not contain `*`, the request is rejected.\n214: \n215: ### 3.2 Concurrency\n216: \n217: The FinOps proxy handles concurrent inference requests using an async-safe state management approach:\n218: - All state mutations (steps 10, 11, 12) are serialised via an async mutex\n219: - The `pending_calls` counter prevents budget races: the sum of `monthly_total + (pending_calls * max_estimated_cost_per_call)` is checked, not just `monthly_total`\n220: \n221: ---\n222: \n223: ## 4. Ledger Format\n224: \n225: ### 4.1 File Location and Naming\n226: \n227: The ledger file is located at:\n228: ```\n229: {install.state_dir}/{finops.accounting.session_budget_file}\n230: ```\n231: \n232: Default: `state/finops-ledger.json`\n233: \n234: ### 4.2 Format\n235: \n236: The ledger uses **JSON Lines** (JSONL) format: one valid JSON object per line, separated by `\\n`. The file MUST be UTF-8 encoded. Lines MUST NOT exceed 4096 bytes.\n237: \n238: ### 4.3 Schema\n239: \n240: Each ledger entry MUST contain the following fields:\n241: \n242: ```typescript\n243: interface LedgerEntry {\n244:   // ISO 8601 timestamp with milliseconds (UTC)\n245:   timestamp: string;\n246: \n247:   // Session identifier: \"sess_\" + 8 random hex characters\n248:   sessionId: string;\n249: \n250:   // Provider identifier (lowercase, hyphenated)\n251:   provider: string;\n252: \n253:   // Model identifier as returned by the provider\n254:   model: string;\n255: \n256:   // Tokens in the prompt/input\n257:   promptTokens: number;\n258: \n259:   // Tokens in the completion/output\n260:   completionTokens: number;\n261: \n262:   // Pre-call cost estimate in config.budget.currency\n263:   estimatedCost: number;\n264: \n265:   // Post-call actual cost in config.budget.currency\n266:   actualCost: number;\n267: \n268:   // ISO 4217 currency code\n269:   currency: string;\n270: \n271:   // Running total for this session in currency units\n272:   sessionTotal: number;\n273: \n274:   // Running total for the calendar month in currency units\n275:   monthlyTotal: number;\n276: \n277:   // Total call count for this session (1-indexed)\n278:   callCount: number;\n279: \n280:   // Optional event identifier for system-generated entries (e.g. \"MONTHLY_RESET\")\n281:   event?: string;\n282: }\n283: ```\n284: \n285: ### 4.4 Example Ledger File\n286: \n287: ```jsonl\n288: {\"timestamp\":\"2025-01-15T14:01:22.001Z\",\"sessionId\":\"sess_a1b2c3d4\",\"provider\":\"foundry-local\",\"model\":\"phi-3.5-mini\",\"promptTokens\":312,\"completionTokens\":89,\"estimatedCost\":0.0,\"actualCost\":0.0,\"currency\":\"GBP\",\"sessionTotal\":0.0,\"monthlyTotal\":0.0,\"callCount\":1}\n289: {\"timestamp\":\"2025-01-15T14:05:44.332Z\",\"sessionId\":\"sess_a1b2c3d4\",\"provider\":\"foundry-local\",\"model\":\"phi-3.5-mini\",\"promptTokens\":256,\"completionTokens\":112,\"estimatedCost\":0.0,\"actualCost\":0.0,\"currency\":\"GBP\",\"sessionTotal\":0.0,\"monthlyTotal\":0.0,\"callCount\":2}\n290: {\"timestamp\":\"2025-01-15T14:18:09.887Z\",\"sessionId\":\"sess_a1b2c3d4\",\"provider\":\"groq\",\"model\":\"llama-3.1-8b-instant\",\"promptTokens\":640,\"completionTokens\":180,\"estimatedCost\":0.000082,\"actualCost\":0.000101,\"currency\":\"GBP\",\"sessionTotal\":0.000101,\"monthlyTotal\":0.000101,\"callCount\":3}\n291: {\"timestamp\":\"2025-01-15T14:22:31.110Z\",\"sessionId\":\"sess_a1b2c3d4\",\"provider\":\"groq\",\"model\":\"llama-3.1-8b-instant\",\"promptTokens\":512,\"completionTokens\":220,\"estimatedCost\":0.000066,\"actualCost\":0.000091,\"currency\":\"GBP\",\"sessionTotal\":0.000192,\"monthlyTotal\":0.000192,\"callCount\":4}\n292: ```\n293: \n294: ### 4.5 Ledger Integrity\n295: \n296: The Supervisor maintains a SHA-256 rolling hash of the ledger file, updated after each write. The hash is stored at `{state_dir}/ledger-hash.txt`. On startup, if `state/finops-ledger.json` exists, its hash is recomputed and compared with the stored hash. If they differ, the Supervisor logs a warning (`LEDGER_INTEGRITY_WARNING`) and records the discrepancy in the Supervisor log but does NOT halt - the ledger may have been copied or inspected by the institution.\n297: \n298: ---\n299: \n300: ## 5. Alert Delivery Mechanism\n301: \n302: ### 5.1 Alert Payload\n303: \n304: All alert deliveries use the same structured payload:\n305: \n306: ```typescript\n307: interface AlertPayload {\n308:   alertType: \"warn\" | \"kill\";\n309:   timestamp: string;          // ISO 8601 UTC\n310:   sessionId: string;\n311:   studentIdentifier: string;  // hash of system username, not PII\n312:   monthlyTotal: number;\n313:   monthlyLimit: number;\n314:   fraction: number;           // monthlyTotal / monthlyLimit\n315:   currency: string;\n316:   callCount: number;\n317:   forgeFile: string;          // path to the .forge file\n318: }\n319: ```\n320: \n321: ### 5.2 Console Delivery\n322: \n323: When `notify` includes `\"console\"`, the Supervisor renders a prominent banner in:\n324: 1. The PDE terminal (via ANSI escape codes)\n325: 2. The IDE status bar (via the Supervisor IDE extension API)\n326: 3. The Evidence Panel notification area\n327: \n328: **Warning banner (warn_at threshold):**\n329: ```\n330: ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n331: ║  ⚠  FORGE FINOPS WARNING                                         ║\n332: ║  You have used 80% of your monthly AI inference budget.          ║\n333: ║  Monthly spend: £0.0016 of £0.0020 limit                        ║\n334: ║  Remaining calls (estimated): ~20                                ║\n335: ║  Local models remain available at no cost.                       ║\n336: ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n337: ```\n338: \n339: **Kill banner (kill_at threshold):**\n340: ```\n341: ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n342: ║  🛑  FORGE FINOPS: CLOUD INFERENCE SUSPENDED                     ║\n343: ║  Monthly cloud AI budget exhausted (£0.0020 / £0.0020).         ║\n344: ║  Cloud inference is disabled for this session.                   ║\n345: ║  Local models (Foundry Local, ONNX WebNN) remain available.      ║\n346: ║  Contact your teacher to review budget settings.                 ║\n347: ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n348: ```\n349: \n350: ### 5.3 Email Delivery\n351: \n352: When `notify` includes `\"email\"`, the Supervisor sends an email via SMTP. SMTP credentials are configured via environment variables (`FORGE_SMTP_HOST`, `FORGE_SMTP_PORT`, `FORGE_SMTP_USER`, `FORGE_SMTP_PASS`, `FORGE_ALERT_EMAIL_TO`). These MUST NOT appear in the `.forge` file.\n353: \n354: The email:\n355: - Subject: `[FORGE FINOPS] Budget ${alertType === 'warn' ? 'Warning' : 'Exhausted'} - Session ${sessionId}`\n356: - Body: Plain text rendering of the alert payload\n357: - MUST be delivered within 60 seconds of the threshold being crossed\n358: - If SMTP fails, the failure is logged and delivery is retried once after 5 minutes\n359: \n360: ### 5.4 Webhook Delivery\n361: \n362: When `notify` includes `\"webhook\"`, the Supervisor sends an HTTP POST to the URL in the `FORGE_ALERT_WEBHOOK` environment variable.\n363: \n364: Request:\n365: ```\n366: POST {FORGE_ALERT_WEBHOOK}\n367: Content-Type: application/json\n368: X-SDTP-Alert-Type: warn|kill\n369: X-SDTP-Session-ID: {sessionId}\n370: X-SDTP-Signature: {HMAC-SHA256 of body using FORGE_ALERT_WEBHOOK_SECRET}\n371: \n372: {AlertPayload as JSON}\n373: ```\n374: \n375: The receiving server SHOULD verify the `X-SDTP-Signature` header. If `FORGE_ALERT_WEBHOOK_SECRET` is not set, the signature header is omitted and the Supervisor logs a warning.\n376: \n377: Webhook delivery is attempted with a 5-second timeout and one retry. Failure to deliver a webhook alert is logged but does not affect FinOps enforcement behaviour.\n378: \n379: ---\n380: \n381: ## 6. Kill Switch Behaviour\n382: \n383: ### 6.1 What the Kill Switch Does\n384: \n385: When the Kill Switch is activated (monthly spend reaches `kill_at` fraction of `max_monthly_cloud`):\n386: \n387: 1. The `state.kill_switch_active = true` flag is set in the in-memory FinOps state\n388: 2. All subsequent pre-call checks for **cloud providers** return `{ error: \"budget_exceeded\" }` immediately, without forwarding the request\n389: 3. The FinOps proxy continues to serve **local provider** requests normally (`foundry-local`, `onnx-webnn`)\n390: 4. The PDE continues running - the student's development environment is NOT interrupted\n391: 5. Kill switch state is persisted to `{state_dir}/finops-state.json` so it survives Supervisor restarts\n392: \n393: ### 6.2 What the Kill Switch Does NOT Do\n394: \n395: - **Does NOT crash the environment** - students can continue coding without inference\n396: - **Does NOT stop local inference** - on-device models are always available\n397: - **Does NOT delete the ledger** - accounting data is preserved for institutional review\n398: - **Does NOT prevent export** - the student can still export their evidence portfolio\n399: \n400: ### 6.3 Graceful Degradation\n401: \n402: Applications using the SDTP inference SDK receive a structured error when the Kill Switch is active:\n403: \n404: ```json\n405: {\n406:   \"error\": \"budget_exceeded\",\n407:   \"code\": \"FORGE_FINOPS_KILL\",\n408:   \"message\": \"Cloud inference budget exhausted. Local models remain available.\",\n409:   \"localAvailable\": true,\n410:   \"suggestedProvider\": \"foundry-local\",\n411:   \"monthlyTotal\": 0.0020,\n412:   \"monthlyLimit\": 0.0020,\n413:   \"currency\": \"GBP\"\n414: }\n415: ```\n416: \n417: The SDK's `useInference` hook automatically falls back to local providers when this error is received if `inference.prefer` is `local` or `auto`. If `inference.prefer` is `cloud` and the Kill Switch is active, the hook returns the error to the application for user-facing handling.\n418: \n419: ### 6.4 Kill Switch Reset\n420: \n421: The Kill Switch resets automatically at the start of a new calendar month (UTC midnight on the first of the month). The reset:\n422: 1. Sets `state.kill_switch_active = false`\n423: 2. Resets `state.monthly_total` to `0.00`\n424: 3. Resets `state.warn_alert_sent` and `state.kill_alert_sent` to `false`\n425: 4. Appends a reset record to the ledger:\n426: \n427: ```json\n428: {\"timestamp\":\"2025-02-01T00:00:00.000Z\",\"sessionId\":\"sess_auto\",\"provider\":\"system\",\"model\":\"none\",\"promptTokens\":0,\"completionTokens\":0,\"estimatedCost\":0.0,\"actualCost\":0.0,\"currency\":\"GBP\",\"sessionTotal\":0.0,\"monthlyTotal\":0.0,\"callCount\":0,\"event\":\"MONTHLY_RESET\"}\n429: ```\n430: \n431: ---\n432: \n433: ## 7. Session vs Monthly Accounting\n434: \n435: The FinOps proxy maintains two independent accounting scopes:\n436: \n437: ### 7.1 Session Accounting\n438: \n439: A **session** begins when `forge up` starts the PDE and ends when `forge down` stops it. Session-scoped counters:\n440: - `session_total` - total cost incurred in this session\n441: - `session_call_count` - total inference calls in this session\n442: \n443: Session totals are displayed in the PDE's Evidence Panel. They are useful for students to understand the cost of a single working session. Session data is included in every ledger entry.\n444: \n445: Session state is NOT persisted across PDE restarts. Each `forge up` begins a new session with a new `sessionId`.\n446: \n447: ### 7.2 Monthly Accounting\n448: \n449: The **monthly** scope covers all sessions within a calendar month (UTC). Monthly-scoped counters:\n450: - `monthly_total` - cumulative cost across all sessions this month\n451: \n452: Monthly state IS persisted to `{state_dir}/finops-state.json` and survives PDE restarts within the same month. On each `forge up`, the Supervisor reads `finops-state.json` and initialises `monthly_total` from the persisted value if the persisted timestamp is within the current calendar month.\n453: \n454: ### 7.3 Accounting Scope Table\n455: \n456: | Counter | Scope | Persisted | Reset Trigger |\n457: |---------|-------|-----------|---------------|\n458: | `session_total` | Session | No | `forge up` |\n459: | `session_call_count` | Session | No | `forge up` |\n460: | `monthly_total` | Calendar month | Yes (`finops-state.json`) | 1st of month (UTC) |\n461: | `warn_alert_sent` | Calendar month | Yes | 1st of month (UTC) |\n462: | `kill_alert_sent` | Calendar month | Yes | 1st of month (UTC) |\n463: | `kill_switch_active` | Calendar month | Yes | 1st of month (UTC) |\n464: \n465: ### 7.4 Multi-Student Accounting\n466: \n467: When multiple students share an institution's API key (a common pattern in classroom environments), the FinOps proxy tracks spend per student using the `studentIdentifier` field (a hash of the system username). Institution administrators can aggregate the `monthlyTotal` fields across ledger files for all students to compute per-cohort cloud spend.\n468: \n469: The SDTP CLI provides `forge report` which aggregates ledger files and produces a summary:\n470: \n471: ```\n472: $ forge report --cohort /path/to/student-workspaces --month 2025-01\n473: SDTP FinOps Monthly Report - January 2025\n474: ══════════════════════════════════════════\n475: Students:          30\n476: Total sessions:    187\n477: Total API calls:   1,204\n478:   ├── Local:        1,089 (90.4%)\n479:   └── Cloud:          115 (9.6%)\n480: Total cloud spend: £0.0138 GBP\n481: Average per student: £0.0005 GBP\n482: Budget utilisation: 6.9% of £0.20 cohort limit\n483: ```\n484: \n485: ---\n486: \n487: ## 8. Provider Cost Table\n488: \n489: The following table reflects the pricing used by the FinOps proxy as of the specification date. Prices in the Registry are updated when providers publish new pricing. All prices are in GBP per 1,000 tokens, converted from provider-published USD prices at the prevailing exchange rate.\n490: \n491: | Provider ID | Description | Input (per 1k tokens) | Output (per 1k tokens) | Notes |\n492: |-------------|-------------|----------------------|------------------------|-------|\n493: | `foundry-local` | Microsoft Foundry Local (on-device) | £0.00 | £0.00 | Runs entirely on-device; no data leaves the machine |\n494: | `onnx-webnn` | ONNX Runtime with WebNN (in-browser) | £0.00 | £0.00 | Runs in WebAssembly/WebNN; no network calls |\n495: | `groq` | Groq Cloud API (Llama 3.1 8B Instant) | ~£0.00006 | ~£0.00009 | Approximate; input and output rates differ; see Registry for current price |\n496: | `cerebras` | Cerebras Cloud API (Llama 3.1 8B) | ~£0.00006 | ~£0.00009 | Approximate; input and output rates differ; see Registry for current price |\n497: | `openai` | OpenAI API (GPT-4o Mini) | ~£0.00012 | ~£0.00048 | Blocked by default; requires explicit `allowed_providers` |\n498: | `anthropic` | Anthropic API (Claude Haiku) | ~£0.00020 | ~£0.00100 | Blocked by default; requires explicit `allowed_providers` |\n499: \n500: ### 8.1 Per-Call Cost Estimates\n501: \n502: For typical student coding assistance calls (512 prompt tokens, 256 completion tokens):\n503: \n504: | Provider | Estimated Cost Per Call | Calls per £1 | Notes |\n505: |----------|------------------------|--------------|-------|\n506: | `foundry-local` | £0.00 | Unlimited | Recommended default |\n507: | `onnx-webnn` | £0.00 | Unlimited | Recommended for browser-only environments |\n508: | `groq` | ~£0.0001 | ~10,000 | Very low cost; suitable for classroom budgets |\n509: | `cerebras` | ~£0.0001 | ~10,000 | Very low cost; suitable for classroom budgets |\n510: | `openai` | ~£0.0002 | ~5,000 | Moderate cost; needs institutional budget |\n511: | `anthropic` | ~£0.0004 | ~2,500 | Higher cost; needs institutional budget |\n512: \n513: ### 8.2 Recommended Budget Settings\n514: \n515: For a typical 15-week semester with 2-hour weekly practical sessions:\n516: \n517: | Scenario | Recommended `max_monthly_cloud` | Notes |\n518: |----------|--------------------------------|-------|\n519: | Local-only (zero spend) | `0.00` | Default; fully private |\n520: | Light cloud (Groq/Cerebras) | `0.50` | ~5,000 calls/month; 33 calls/session |\n521: | Moderate cloud | `2.00` | ~20,000 calls/month |\n522: | Institution-managed | _(set by IT policy)_ | Use `max_inference_calls` as a call-count backstop |\n523: \n524: ---\n525: \n526: ## 9. Accounting API\n527: \n528: The Supervisor exposes a read-only FinOps API at `http://127.0.0.1:{ports.supervisor}/api/finops/`. Authentication requires the Supervisor bearer token.\n529: \n530: ### `GET /api/finops/status`\n531: \n532: Returns the current FinOps state:\n533: \n534: ```json\n535: {\n536:   \"sessionId\": \"sess_a1b2c3d4\",\n537:   \"sessionTotal\": 0.000192,\n538:   \"monthlyTotal\": 0.000192,\n539:   \"sessionCallCount\": 4,\n540:   \"budget\": {\n541:     \"max_monthly_cloud\": 2.00,\n542:     \"currency\": \"GBP\"\n543:   },\n544:   \"fraction\": 0.000096,\n545:   \"killSwitchActive\": false,\n546:   \"warnAlertSent\": false,\n547:   \"killAlertSent\": false\n548: }\n549: ```\n550: \n551: ### `GET /api/finops/ledger`\n552: \n553: Returns the full ledger as an array of JSON objects (parsed from JSONL). Supports query parameters `?since={ISO8601}&limit={n}`.\n554: \n555: ### `GET /api/finops/report`\n556: \n557: Returns a summary report for the current month:\n558: \n559: ```json\n560: {\n561:   \"month\": \"2025-01\",\n562:   \"totalCalls\": 4,\n563:   \"localCalls\": 2,\n564:   \"cloudCalls\": 2,\n565:   \"totalCost\": 0.000192,\n566:   \"currency\": \"GBP\",\n567:   \"providers\": {\n568:     \"foundry-local\": { \"calls\": 2, \"cost\": 0.0 },\n569:     \"groq\": { \"calls\": 2, \"cost\": 0.000192 }\n570:   }\n571: }\n572: ```\n573: \n574: ---\n575: \n576: ## 10. Configuration Reference\n577: \n578: Full `finops:` section configuration reference (from `SPECIFICATION.md`):\n579: \n580: ```yaml\n581: finops:\n582:   budget:\n583:     max_monthly_cloud: 2.00     # number, default 0.00\n584:     max_inference_calls: 200    # integer, optional\n585:     currency: GBP               # ISO 4217, default GBP\n586: \n587:   inference:\n588:     prefer: local               # local | cloud | auto, default local\n589:     allowed_providers:          # array, default all registered providers\n590:      - foundry-local\n591:      - onnx-webnn\n592:      - groq\n593:     blocked_providers: []       # array, default empty\n594:     model_constraints:          # map, optional\n595:       groq: \"llama-3.1-8b-instant\"\n596: \n597:   alerts:\n598:     warn_at: 0.80               # fraction, default 0.80\n599:     kill_at: 1.00               # fraction, default 1.00\n600:     notify:                     # array, default [\"console\"]\n601:      - console\n602:      - webhook\n603: \n604:   accounting:\n605:     log_inference_costs: true           # boolean, default true\n606:     session_budget_file: state/finops-ledger.json  # filename, default shown\n607: ```\n608: \n609: ---\n610: \n611: ## 11. Audit and Compliance\n612: \n613: ### 11.1 Ledger Retention\n614: \n615: Institutions MUST retain FinOps ledger files for a minimum of **1 academic year** after the associated assessment period ends. Ledger files constitute part of the academic integrity audit trail and may be requested by awarding bodies during verification exercises.\n616: \n617: ### 11.2 Data Protection\n618: \n619: The ledger MUST NOT contain:\n620: - Student names\n621: - Student email addresses\n622: - Student ID numbers\n623: - Raw inference prompts or responses\n624: - Any other Personal Identifiable Information (PII)\n625: \n626: The `studentIdentifier` field in alert payloads uses a one-way hash (SHA-256 of username with a per-institution salt). The mapping from hash to student identity is held by the institution's IT system, not by SDTP.\n627: \n628: ### 11.3 Awarding Body Reporting\n629: \n630: When a `curriculum.board` is set, the `forge report --awarding-body` command generates a report formatted for the relevant awarding body. For WJEC and AQA, this includes:\n631: - Total AI assistance calls per SDLC phase (as identified from Evidence Panel section tags)\n632: - Fraction of code flagged as AI-assisted vs student-authored\n633: - Attestation statement for the portfolio\n634: \n635: This report does not constitute an authenticity certificate; it is an informational audit aid.\n636: \n637: ---\n638: \n639: *This document is maintained by the SDTP Working Group. For pricing table updates, see the Registry at `https://github.com/andiekobbietks/lampforge-runtime/releases`.*\n\n(End of file - total 639 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
