      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\docs\\sovereign-ai-inference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Sovereign AI Inference: Engineering Rationale & Documentation\n2: \n3: This document outlines the technical architecture and strategic rationale for the **Sovereign AI Inference** system within LAMPForge. By moving LLM inference directly into the Microsoft Edge browser (v146+), we achieve a defensible pedagogical and economic position that cloud-based competitors cannot replicate.\n4: \n5: ## 1. The Rationale: Why Edge-in-Browser?\n6: \n7: The decision to run inference natively in the browser is grounded in three core pillars:\n8: \n9: ### A. Unit Economics ($0 Marginal Cost)\n10: Traditional AI applications pay a \"token tax\" to providers like OpenAI or Anthropic for every single user interaction. In a classroom of 30 students making hundreds of queries per hour, these costs become prohibitive.\n11: *   **Engineering Solution:** By using the Edge Prompt API (Windows ML) and local ONNX runtimes, the student's local machine provides the compute. \n12: *   **Rationale:** Marginal cost for inference drops to **$0.00**, allowing for unlimited experimentation within the Pedagogical Development Environment (PDE) without budget liability.\n13: \n14: ### B. Data Sovereignty & Regulatory Compliance\n15: Educational institutions have strict HIPAA, GDPR, and COPPA requirements. Sending student code or intent data to a third-party server is a significant procurement blocker.\n16: *   **Engineering Solution:** 0 bytes of prompt or output data leave the local device. The inference process is air-gapped from cloud scrutiny.\n17: *   **Rationale:** This creates an absolute **Regulatory Moat**, making LAMPForge the only compliant choice for strictly sandboxed educational environments.\n18: \n19: ### C. Hardware Life Extension\n20: Many schools are equipped with depreciated \"e-waste\" hardware (Celeron-grade CPUs). Cloud-based IDEs require high-speed, persistent internet which these environments often lack.\n21: *   **Engineering Solution:** We leverage WebNN and WebGPU acceleration to \"hijack\" the local GPU (even integrated ones) to run models like Phi-4-mini natively.\n22: *   **Rationale:** This reclaims millions of dollars of existing physical infrastructure, providing a **Physical Infrastructure Moat**.\n23: \n24: ---\n25: \n26: ## 2. Visual Documentation & Keyframes\n27: \n28: ### The Sovereign Model Catalogue\n29: The Admin panel features a dedicated catalogue where educators can manage the \"Software Defined Training Provisioning\" (SDTP) protocol.\n30: \n31: ![Sovereign AI Model Catalogue](media/catalogue_view.webp)\n32: *Caption: The Sovereign Catalogue view showing the diverse array of local-first models. Each card details the architecture (ONNX, Browser Native, GGUF) and the specific pedagogical role (Routing, Synthesis, Architecture).*\n33: \n34: ### Real-Time Inference Testing\n35: Users can validate model performance directly within the catalogue to ensure the \"Moat\" is functioning correctly on local hardware.\n36: \n37: ![Interactive Inference Testing](media/inference_demo.webp)\n38: *Caption: A live demonstration of the \"Test Model\" feature. Here, a prompt is being routed to the browser-native Windows ML engine. The response is generated with zero latency and zero API cost.*\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## 3. How It Works: The Technical Stack\n43: \n44: The inference engine follows an **Inference Cascade** logic:\n45: \n46: 1.  **Level 1: Browser Native (`window.ai`)**\n47:     *   Leverages the experimental Prompt API and Windows ML.\n48:     *   Target Model: **Phi-4-mini (3.8B)**.\n49:     *   *Best for: General reasoning and summarization.*\n50: \n51: 2.  **Level 2: ONNX Runtime Web (WebNN/WebGPU)**\n52:     *   Uses highly optimized ONNX weights running through the browser's hardware acceleration layers.\n53:     *   Target Model: **Forge Router Micro**.\n54:     *   *Best for: Task-specific routing and protocol compilation.*\n55: \n56: 3.  **Level 3: FinOps Controlled Fallback**\n57:     *   If local hardware is insufficient, the system checks the SDTP budget firewall before allowing a limited cloud call.\n58: \n59: ---\n60: \n61: *This document serves as technical evidence of LAMPForge's commitment to Sovereign Infrastructure and Engineering Excellence.*\n\n(End of file - total 61 lines)\n</content>",
