      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\\\internal\\\\docs-private\\\\sovereign_pde_architecture.md\", \"offset\": 700, \"limit\": 120}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\internal\\docs-private\\sovereign_pde_architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n700: ### What We Have: The Olive Pipeline\n701: \n702: Microsoft Olive is a model optimisation framework. We have an Olive\n703: configuration (`.olive-cache/default_workflow/olive_config.json`) that:\n704: \n705: 1. Takes a HuggingFace model (`arch-router-raw-local`)\n706: 2. Converts it to ONNX format (Open Neural Network Exchange)\n707: 3. Applies peephole optimisation (removes redundant operations)\n708: 4. Applies transformer optimisation\n709: 5. Quantises to INT4 (reduces model size by 4x, speeds up CPU inference)\n710: 6. Outputs a model that runs on `CPUExecutionProvider` only\n711: \n712: The result is a ~50MB model that can classify user intent in <1 second on a\n713: typical school laptop CPU.\n714: \n715: ### The Inference Cascade\n716: \n717: Our AI pipeline (`sdk/forge-ai.ts`) implements a 4-stage fallback:\n718: \n719: ```\n720: Stage 1: ONNX Runtime Web (browser)\n721: ├── Runs in the browser via WebAssembly\n722: ├── Uses the INT4 quantised model from Olive\n723: ├── Zero network, zero cost, zero latency (beyond compute)\n724: ├── WebNN backend if available (uses DirectML on Windows)\n725: ├── WASM backend as fallback (pure CPU)\n726: └── 8-second timeout, then fall through\n727: \n728: Stage 2: Foundry Local (localhost)\n729: ├── Microsoft's local inference runtime\n730: ├── Runs as a system service or user-space process\n731: ├── Much faster than browser WASM\n732: ├── Uses CPU, NPU, or GPU depending on hardware\n733: └── Requires Foundry to be installed\n734: \n735: Stage 3: Groq Cloud (remote)\n736: ├── Groq's ultra-fast inference API\n737: ├── Requires internet and API key\n738: ├── Subject to FinOps budget limits\n739: └── Used only when local options fail\n740: \n741: Stage 4: Cerebras Cloud (remote)\n742: ├── Cerebras' inference API\n743: ├── Same constraints as Groq\n744: └── Final fallback\n745: ```\n746: \n747: Each stage is wrapped by the FinOps Guard, which checks the session budget\n748: before allowing any inference call. If the budget is $0.00 (as in the\n749: air-gapped example), Stages 3 and 4 are never reached.\n750: \n751: ### WebNN: The CPU/NPU/GPU Abstraction\n752: \n753: **WebNN** (Web Neural Network API) is a W3C specification (Candidate\n754: Recommendation as of 2024) that provides a hardware abstraction layer for\n755: neural network inference in the browser:\n756: \n757: ```\n758: Your AI model (ONNX)\n759:        |\n760:        v\n761:   WebNN API (browser)\n762:        |\n763:        +--> DirectML (Windows) --> GPU or NPU or CPU\n764:        |\n765:        +--> CoreML (macOS) --> Apple Neural Engine or GPU or CPU\n766:        |\n767:        +--> XNNPACK (Linux) --> CPU\n768:        |\n769:        +--> WASM (fallback) --> CPU via WebAssembly\n770: ```\n771: \n772: When we enable `--enable-features=WebMachineLearningNeuralNetwork` in our\n773: portable Edge, we unlock WebNN. The ONNX Runtime Web library automatically\n774: selects the best backend:\n775: \n776: 1. If the machine has a discrete GPU -> DirectML uses the GPU\n777: 2. If the machine has an NPU (Intel Meteor Lake, Qualcomm Snapdragon) -> DirectML uses the NPU\n778: 3. If neither -> WASM backend runs on the CPU\n779: \n780: This is why the portable Edge flags matter. Without them, WebNN is not\n781: available, and inference falls back to the slower WASM-only path.\n782: \n783: ### CPU Performance: Is It Good Enough?\n784: \n785: For our use case, yes:\n786: \n787: - **Route classification** (Stage 1): The Olive-optimised INT4 model\n788:   classifies intent in 200-800ms on a typical i5 laptop CPU. This is fast\n789:   enough for a submit button workflow (not real-time streaming).\n790: \n791: - **Blueprint generation** (Stage 2): For a 500-token response from Foundry\n792:   Local using a 7B parameter model (e.g., Phi-3-mini), expect 2-5 seconds\n793:   on a modern CPU. Again, acceptable for a non-interactive generation step.\n794: \n795: - **In-browser ONNX**: The WASM execution provider processes ~50-200 tokens\n796:   per second on a modern CPU for small models (<1B params). The WebNN\n797:   provider on the same hardware can be 2-5x faster because it uses optimised\n798:   CPU instructions (AVX512, AVX-VNNI) directly.\n799: \n800: For comparison, Kasm streams video at 30fps, which requires far more CPU than\n801: our structured data approach.\n802: \n803: ---\n804: \n805: ## 11. The Full Stack Diagram\n806: \n807: ```\n808: ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n809: │                        Student's Machine                             │\n810: │                                                                      │\n811: │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │\n812: │  │              Portable Edge (User-Space, No Admin)              │  │\n813: │  │  Flags: WebGPU | WebNN | WASM | SharedArrayBuffer | IWA       │  │\n814: │  │                                                                │  │\n815: │  │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │  │\n816: │  │  │                   LAMPForge PWA                         │    │  │\n817: │  │  │                                                        │    │  │\n818: │  │  │  ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ │    │  │\n819: │  │  │  │  Code    │ │ Terminal │ │   SQL    │ │   AI    │  │    │  │\n\n(Showing lines 700-819 of 924. Use offset=820 to continue.)\n</content>",
